🌟 GitHub Actions, Docker, ECS, and ECR Project
Welcome to the GitHub Actions Tutorial repository! This project will walk you through setting up a continuous deployment pipeline using GitHub Actions, Docker, ECS, and ECR.

📚 Table of Contents
Project Overview
Setup Instructions
Continuous Deployment
Resources
Contributing
License
🚀 Project Overview
This project demonstrates a simple pipeline setup using GitHub Actions to automate the deployment of a Docker container to Amazon ECS using ECR for container storage. Perfect for those eager to streamline their cloud deployments!

🛠 Setup Instructions
Create Project Directory

mkdir github-actions-tutorial
Docker Setup

Create a Dockerfile and build the image:
bash
Copy code
docker build -t github-tutorial-image .
Run a Container for Testing

Launch a simple Docker container:
bash
Copy code
docker run -d -p 80:80 github-tutorial-image
Amazon ECR Setup

Via AWS Console: Create a new ECR repository.
Via AWS CLI:
Authenticate:
bash
Copy code
aws configure
Create repository:
bash
Copy code
aws ecr create-repository --repository-name github-actions-tuto
Upload Docker Image to ECR

Login to ECR:
bash
Copy code
aws ecr get-login-password --region us-east-1 | docker login --username AWS --password-stdin 637423409202.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com
Tag and push the image:
bash
Copy code
docker tag github-tutorial-image:latest 637423409202.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/github-tutorial-image:latest
docker push 637423409202.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/github-tutorial-image:latest
Set Up GitHub Repository

Create a new repo and push your code.
ECS Cluster Creation

Via CLI:
bash
Copy code
aws ecs create-cluster --cluster-name github-actions-tutorial-ecs-cluster
Via AWS Console: Use the console interface to create your cluster.
AWS Configuration

Create an .aws folder and a task definition file.
Configure CloudWatch Logs and IAM roles for ECS tasks.
🔄 Continuous Deployment
GitHub Actions Workflow
Set up a workflow for automatic deployment to ECS upon git push.
Configure AWS secrets in your GitHub repository settings.
